---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Callout from '../components/Callout.astro';
import { url } from '../lib/url';

const title = 'The Groundwork flywheel';
const description =
  'How the skill, CLI, pre-commit hook, and per-command moves orchestrate together. The four roles, the cadence, the automation picture, and where the wins come from.';
---

<Base title={title} description={description}>
  <div class="container flywheel">
    <h1>The Groundwork flywheel</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      Groundwork is a skill. Nine commands. A CLI with twelve rules. A
      pre-commit hook. Templates. The parts list lives at
      <a href={url('commands/')}>/commands</a> and
      <a href={url('cli/')}>/cli</a>. This page is the assembly diagram:
      how the pieces fit, when each runs, what stays human.
    </p>

    <p class="forward-link">
      New to the nine? <a href={url('commands/')}>/commands</a> names them
      in a sentence each. The names below assume you have met them.
    </p>

    <figure class="flywheel-diagram">
      <svg viewBox="50 50 500 500" role="img" aria-labelledby="fw-title" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
        <title id="fw-title">A weighted flywheel: four roles around a hub, an amber rotation sweep across the rim.</title>
        <defs>
          <marker id="fw-arrow" markerWidth="28" markerHeight="24" refX="0" refY="12" orient="auto" markerUnits="userSpaceOnUse">
            <path d="M 0 0 L 28 12 L 0 24 Z" class="fw-arrow-head" />
          </marker>
        </defs>

        <path class="fw-rim" fill-rule="evenodd"
              d="M 300 50 A 250 250 0 1 0 300 550 A 250 250 0 1 0 300 50 Z
                 M 300 95 A 205 205 0 1 1 300 505 A 205 205 0 1 1 300 95 Z" />

        <g class="fw-spokes">
          <line x1="322.6" y1="277.4" x2="452.0" y2="148.0" />
          <line x1="277.4" y1="277.4" x2="148.0" y2="148.0" />
          <line x1="322.6" y1="322.6" x2="452.0" y2="452.0" />
          <line x1="277.4" y1="322.6" x2="148.0" y2="452.0" />
        </g>

        <circle class="fw-hub-disc" cx="300" cy="300" r="32" />
        <circle class="fw-hub-spark" cx="300" cy="300" r="6" />

        <text class="fw-role" x="300" y="155" text-anchor="middle">AUTHOR</text>
        <text class="fw-role" x="440" y="292" text-anchor="middle">GUIDE</text>
        <text class="fw-role" x="300" y="395" text-anchor="middle">ENFORCE</text>
        <text class="fw-role" x="160" y="292" text-anchor="middle">ORIENT</text>

        <g class="fw-cmd">
          <text x="300" y="188" text-anchor="middle">init · document</text>
          <text x="300" y="212" text-anchor="middle">scope · mcp · verify</text>

          <text x="440" y="322" text-anchor="middle">plan</text>
          <text x="440" y="346" text-anchor="middle">adr</text>

          <text x="300" y="428" text-anchor="middle">CLI detect · pre-commit</text>
          <text x="300" y="452" text-anchor="middle">drift hook</text>

          <text x="160" y="322" text-anchor="middle">onboard</text>
          <text x="160" y="346" text-anchor="middle">audit</text>
        </g>

        <g class="fw-sweep-rot">
          <path class="fw-sweep" marker-end="url(#fw-arrow)"
                d="M 300 72.5 A 227.5 227.5 0 0 1 527.5 300" />
        </g>
      </svg>
      <figcaption>
        Cadence runs clockwise. Lay the rails. Steer the change. Catch the
        slip on commit. Re-ground before drift compounds.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2 id="four-roles">The four roles</h2>
    <p>
      Every Groundwork piece sits in one of four roles. Knowing which is
      which lets you reason about cadence: enforce-tier pieces run on every
      commit; orient-tier pieces run on the calendar; guide-tier pieces run
      inside a single change.
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Role</th><th>Pieces</th><th>Verb</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Author</strong></td>
          <td><code>init</code>, <code>document</code>, <code>scope</code>, <code>mcp</code>, <code>verify</code></td>
          <td>Lay the rails.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Guide</strong></td>
          <td><code>plan</code>, <code>adr</code></td>
          <td>Steer the change.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Enforce</strong></td>
          <td>CLI <code>detect</code>, pre-commit hook, drift hook, the <code>conventions-drift</code> and <code>stale-claude-md</code> rules</td>
          <td>Catch the slip.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Orient</strong></td>
          <td><code>onboard</code>, <code>audit</code></td>
          <td>Re-ground.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      Each role has its own cadence. Run them on the wrong rhythm and you
      either burn time on the cheap moves or skip the expensive ones. Both
      fail.
    </p>

    <h2 id="cadence">Cadence</h2>
    <p>
      Map a trigger to a move. The <em>Who</em> column is the human-vs-automated
      split; the next section names which of those are wired today and which
      are one workflow file away.
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Trigger</th><th>What to run</th><th>Why</th><th>Who</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Day 0 of a repo</td>
          <td><a href={url('commands/init/')}><code>init</code></a>, then <a href={url('commands/verify/')}><code>verify</code></a></td>
          <td>Sets up <code>.context/conventions.md</code>, <code>AGENTS.md</code> with <code>CLAUDE.md</code> symlink, <code>.cursor/rules/</code>, ADR scaffolding, the pre-commit hook.</td>
          <td>You, once</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Every commit</td>
          <td><code>groundwork detect --fail-on P0</code></td>
          <td>Sub-second. P0s never reach <code>main</code>.</td>
          <td>Automated</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Every PR</td>
          <td><code>groundwork detect --fail-on P1</code></td>
          <td>Catches drift rules (<code>conventions-drift</code>, <code>oversized-claude-md</code>, <code>agents-claude-sync</code>, <code>missing-verification</code>).</td>
          <td>Automated</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Every non-trivial change</td>
          <td><a href={url('commands/plan/')}><code>plan</code></a></td>
          <td>Plan Mode contract before code. The cost of skipping is the cost of agents coding the wrong thing.</td>
          <td>Agent, when prompted</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Every architectural decision</td>
          <td><a href={url('commands/adr/')}><code>adr</code></a></td>
          <td>Captures both the choice and the rejected alternatives. The negative-space section is half the value.</td>
          <td>Agent, at the moment</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Stack or convention change</td>
          <td><a href={url('commands/document/')}><code>document</code></a></td>
          <td>Re-emits per-harness files from <code>.context/conventions.md</code>. The CLI's <code>conventions-drift</code> rule pings you if you forget.</td>
          <td>Semi-automated</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>New area of the codebase</td>
          <td><a href={url('commands/scope/')}><code>scope</code></a></td>
          <td>File-pattern-scoped rules; <code>.mdc</code> files carry trigger-level word budgets so they do not bloat.</td>
          <td>You</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>New MCP server</td>
          <td><a href={url('commands/mcp/')}><code>mcp</code></a></td>
          <td>Least-privilege config, HITL policy, audit trail.</td>
          <td>You, per server</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>New agent or teammate</td>
          <td><a href={url('commands/onboard/')}><code>onboard</code></a></td>
          <td>Task-specific orientation brief, not the same as reading <code>CLAUDE.md</code> cold.</td>
          <td>You, at handoff</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Quarterly health check</td>
          <td><a href={url('commands/audit/')}><code>audit</code></a></td>
          <td>Scores AI-readiness; finds gaps the CLI does not have rules for yet (cognitive debt, vague principles, missing negative space).</td>
          <td>You, on the calendar</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2 id="automation">Automation: what runs without you</h2>

    <h3>Automated today</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>
        The <strong>pre-commit hook</strong> installed by
        <a href={url('commands/verify/')}><code>verify</code></a>. Runs
        <code>groundwork detect --fail-on P0</code> against staged context
        files.
      </li>
      <li>
        The <strong>site deploy workflow</strong>
        (<code>.github/workflows/deploy-site.yml</code>), on every push to
        <code>main</code>.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h3>One workflow file away</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>
        A <strong>CI gate</strong> running
        <code>npx @ignitic/groundwork detect --fail-on P1</code> on every
        pull request. Catches drift before review.
      </li>
      <li>
        A <strong>tag-driven CLI publish</strong> workflow firing on
        <code>cli-v*</code> tags, optionally with npm provenance for a
        signed build attestation.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Stays human-triggered</h3>
    <p>
      <code>plan</code>, <code>adr</code>, <code>scope</code>,
      <code>onboard</code>, and <code>audit</code> all stay manual. Each of
      them needs a person or an agent to decide the moment. Automating them
      on a cron produces noise, not signal; they fire when a human says
      "now." Cron jobs are not human. Do not pretend otherwise.
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>The CLI is the only piece that runs without you asking. Everything
      else fires when a human decides the moment.</em>
    </p>

    <h2 id="leverage">Where the wins come from</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>Pre-commit and CI gates on day one.</strong>
        These are the only pieces that protect you from yourself. Without
        them, the rest of Groundwork is voluntary and decays.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><code>plan</code> before any change touching more than three
        files.</strong>
        Cost: thirty seconds. Saves the most expensive error class: agents
        coding without context lock.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>ADRs are the only long memory.</strong>
        Every "we do not do X anymore" survives staffing changes only if
        captured. The negative-space section is half the value.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Foundation files do their work silently.</strong>
        <a href={url('foundation/good-practices/')}>Good practices</a>,
        <a href={url('foundation/anti-patterns/')}>anti-patterns</a>, and
        <a href={url('foundation/cognitive-debt/')}>cognitive debt</a> load
        on every skill invocation. The patterns ride along. Your job is to
        keep them current.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>The split-file architecture from day one.</strong>
        Lean <code>AGENTS.md</code> root, stable rules in
        <code>.claude/rules/&lt;NN&gt;-&lt;name&gt;.md</code>. Retrofitting
        the split later is harder than adopting it now.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><code>document</code> is the spine of the loop.</strong>
        When <code>.context/conventions.md</code> changes, everything else
        regenerates from it. Do not hand-edit <code>CLAUDE.md</code>,
        <code>AGENTS.md</code>, or <code>.cursor/rules/*.mdc</code>; edit
        the canonical source and re-document.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <h2 id="one-sentence">The flywheel, one sentence</h2>
    <Callout label="If you remember one thing" tone="ember">
      <p>
        Author rules once with <code>init</code>, let the CLI guard them on
        every commit, re-author them with <code>document</code> whenever
        conventions shift, use <code>plan</code> and <code>adr</code> to
        keep individual changes honest, and re-orient with
        <code>onboard</code> and <code>audit</code> whenever a new agent or
        a new quarter starts.
      </p>
    </Callout>

    <Callout label="Where to go from here" tone="mute">
      <p>
        For the parts list, see
        <a href={url('commands/')}>the nine commands</a>. For the rules the
        detector enforces, see <a href={url('cli/')}>the CLI page</a>. For
        the model the whole thing rests on, see
        <a href={url('blueprint/')}>the blueprint</a>.
      </p>
    </Callout>
  </div>

  <style>
    .flywheel h2 {
      border-top: 1px solid var(--rule);
      padding-top: 2rem;
      scroll-margin-top: 2rem;
    }
    .flywheel h2:first-of-type { border-top: none; padding-top: 0; }
    .flywheel h3 { scroll-margin-top: 2rem; }

    .flywheel .forward-link {
      margin: -0.25rem 0 1.75rem;
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      color: var(--ink-soft);
    }

    .flywheel-diagram {
      margin: 1rem auto 1.25rem;
      max-width: 600px;
    }
    .flywheel-diagram svg {
      width: 100%;
      height: auto;
      display: block;
    }
    .flywheel-diagram figcaption {
      margin: 0.5rem auto 0;
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      text-align: center;
      font-style: italic;
      line-height: 1.55;
      max-width: 36rem;
    }

    /* The wheel itself: dark filled rim, light interior */
    .flywheel-diagram .fw-rim {
      fill: var(--ink);
    }
    .flywheel-diagram .fw-spokes line {
      stroke: var(--ink);
      stroke-width: 1.25;
      stroke-linecap: round;
    }
    .flywheel-diagram .fw-hub-disc {
      fill: var(--bg);
      stroke: var(--ink);
      stroke-width: 1.5;
    }
    .flywheel-diagram .fw-hub-spark {
      fill: var(--ember);
    }

    /* Role labels and command lists inside the quadrants */
    .flywheel-diagram .fw-role {
      font-size: 22px;
      font-weight: 700;
      letter-spacing: 0.16em;
      fill: var(--ink);
    }
    .flywheel-diagram .fw-cmd text {
      font-family: var(--mono);
      font-size: 14px;
      fill: var(--ink-soft);
    }

    /* The amber rotation sweep, sitting on the dark rim */
    .flywheel-diagram .fw-sweep {
      fill: none;
      stroke: var(--ember);
      stroke-width: 10;
      stroke-linecap: round;
    }
    .flywheel-diagram .fw-arrow-head {
      fill: var(--ember);
    }

    /* One-shot entrance: the sweep traces a full revolution and rests */
    .flywheel-diagram .fw-sweep-rot {
      transform-origin: 300px 300px;
      transform-box: view-box;
      animation: fw-spin 2.4s var(--ease-out-quart) 0.3s both;
    }
    @keyframes fw-spin {
      from { transform: rotate(0deg); }
      to   { transform: rotate(360deg); }
    }
    @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
      .flywheel-diagram .fw-sweep-rot { animation: none; }
    }

    /* Mobile: drop the in-wheel command lists; the cadence table is authoritative */
    @media (max-width: 520px) {
      .flywheel-diagram .fw-cmd { display: none; }
      .flywheel-diagram .fw-role { font-size: 24px; }
    }
  </style>
</Base>
